&lt;a class="reference external image-reference" href="/_images/3762871516221178379.jpg"&gt;&lt;img alt="projects/project-27757/images/3762871516221178379.jpg" src="projects/project-27757/images/3762871516221178379.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a class="reference external image-reference" href="/_images/9897221516920665977.jpg"&gt;&lt;img alt="projects/project-27757/images/9897221516920665977.jpg" src="projects/project-27757/images/9897221516920665977.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight-none notranslate"&gt;&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;The Micro:bit is a pretty decent platform for teaching kids to
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;program, but you can’t really make arcade-style games for it. You only
have two buttons and a 5x5 display. Perhaps enough for a very small
snake game, but that’s pretty much it. That’s why I started working on &lt;a class="reference internal" href="../../../projects/project-21578/#project-21578"&gt;&lt;span class="std std-ref"&gt;PewPew FeatherWing&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; as an alternative platform, but at some point I started wondering if
it’s really impossible to do it on the micro:bit.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When the most recent version of micropython got the ability to use any
pins for I2C, I realized that I can finally connect a display easily.
I could use a HT16K33 and a 8x8 LED matrix like on the PewPew, but I
decided to try something else — a monochrome OLED display, similar to
the one used on many Arduino-based game consoles.&lt;/p&gt;
